wireguardrtc (0.2.5-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * D1.10 follow-ups: make a vanilla-Ubuntu install actually work for
    daemon-side wormhole pairing without manual config rescue.
  * F1 (broker UX): drop the literal `your.broker.example` placeholder
    from the shipped config.  Daemon now refuses to start until the
    admin picks a broker — inline error message names both viable
    options (public 0.peerjs.com vs self-host Docker recipe) so the
    admin doesn't need to consult external docs.
  * F2 (enrollment defaults): ship `[Enrollment]` UNCOMMENTED so the
    out-of-the-box install supports wormhole + token enrollment via
    the broker-mediated default ProvisionScript path.
  * F3 (daemon-managed pairs): `--mint-wormhole` and `--use-wormhole`
    now write a peers.d-style drop-in to
    `/var/lib/wireguardrtc/auto-enrolled.d/` after a successful pair.
    The daemon picks it up and actively maintains the new tunnel.
    Drop-in files are chowned to the daemon user when written as
    root.  Daemon logs a one-line kernel-vs-managed-peer inventory
    after the first poll so admins notice peers that aren't being
    maintained.
  * F4 + F5 (provision-default): the address allocator was silently
    broken by a bash heredoc/herestring redirection quirk (always
    returned pool.hosts()[0]).  Rewrite to pass USED via argv;
    [Interface] Address is now properly reserved.  New
    `WIREGUARDRTC_PROVISION_ASSIGNED_ADDRESS` env var lets the
    wormhole-pair host advertise a specific address to the joiner
    and have provision-default honour it (validating pool membership
    + collision).

 -- Markus Gutschke <gutschke@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 14 May 2026 13:25:00 -0700

wireguardrtc (0.2.4-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Wormhole pairing for the daemon, parity with the Android app
    (D1).  Two new subcommands:
      --mint-wormhole [--label NAME] [--iface IFACE] [--parameters STR]
        prints a 6-letter wormhole code + waits for a peer to dial in;
      --use-wormhole CODE [--iface IFACE]
        types the 6-letter code on a remote machine and joins the host.
    Both sides verify the SAS phrase before committing the new peer.
    Ristretto255 / SPAKE2 / SAS implementation is vendored — no pypi
    dependency for the cryptography.
  * --check-nat subcommand: independent IPv4 / IPv6 classification
    (full-cone / address-restricted / port-restricted / symmetric /
    none-detected) with optional rDNS + ISP enrichment.
  * ProvisionScript hook: wormhole-pair flow now invokes the same
    hook as token-based enrollment, passing the admin-supplied
    parameter string via the new WIREGUARDRTC_PROVISION_PARAMETERS
    environment variable.  Backward-compatible: scripts that read the
    sidecar still work unchanged.
  * Test-only command-line flags (--pubkey-override, --auto-confirm-sas)
    are now gated behind WIREGUARDRTC_ALLOW_TEST_FLAGS=1.  Without
    the gate they're hidden from --help and refuse to run.
  * Documentation: man pages are mirrored as docs/*.md (auto-generated
    from troff).  New docs/provision-scripts.md describes how to
    write a custom ProvisionScript.

 -- Markus Gutschke <gutschke@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 13 May 2026 20:44:00 -0700

wireguardrtc (0.2.3-1) unstable; urgency=high

  * Release blocker: restore daemon from v0.2.0 corruption.  A
    code-cleanup pass in the v0.2.0 restructure stripped ~80
    trailing `()` from function calls plus three test files'
    indentation; the file remained syntax-valid because each
    corrupted site is a legal bound-method reference (e.g. `main`
    instead of `main()` at module bottom).  Every fresh-install of
    v0.2.0's .deb produced a daemon that exited 0 silently and did
    nothing.  Existing v0.1.0 installs kept working only because
    they were still running the old binary; v0.1.0 -> v0.2.0
    upgrades silently broke.
  * Daemon repair touched ~96 call sites across `wireguardrtc`,
    three test files (`25_parallel_stun.py`, `26_candidate_trim.py`,
    `27_candidate_enumerate.py`), and `fabric.sh`'s nine function
    definitions.  Restored `get_public_ipv4_all`'s missing
    `LOG.event` for the PublicIp override (test 09 caught it).
  * Two CI safeguards added: `tests/28_help_smoke.py` (runs
    `wireguardrtc --help` and fails on empty stdout) and
    `tests/29_ast_lint.py` (flags bare Name/Attribute expressions,
    method refs in boolean contexts, and method-shaped attr
    assignments).
  * Full test pass: 175 daemon assertions + 11 fabric end-to-end
    PASS across the unit and shell/fabric suites.

 -- Markus Gutschke <gutschke@users.noreply.github.com>  Wed, 13 May 2026 12:00:00 +0000

wireguardrtc (0.2.0-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Repository restructured to host the daemon and the Android client
    side by side on a unified version tag.  The daemon source moves
    from the repo root to `daemon/`; behaviour is unchanged.
  * Relicensed from MIT to Apache License 2.0 (the daemon's source
    has no GPL or otherwise-incompatible dependencies; Apache 2.0 was
    chosen for its explicit patent grant).
  * Repo renamed from `wireguardrtc` to `wgrtc` to match the Android
    package id and avoid confusion with the trademarked WireGuard name.

